		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			I think with careful tuning this would be a GREAT idea.<br><br>It has the potential to be abused, but it is definitely a great way for servers to start policing themselves.<br><br>Now, specific offenders will be able to have bounties on their heads for the actions they do to the community. Bind rushing, corpse camping, all those types of things can result in bounties. The most hated players on a server will regularily have bounties on their heads. Plus, guilds can collectively make bounties.<br><br>I think a more in depth look at this system is warranted, but it definitely is a good idea to start with.<br><br>Some features I would like to see:<br><br>1. Recurring bounties - Have the option to set the bounty to recurr, and allow a time limit (no more often than hourly or daily, as the lowest possible setting). Say I dislike someone and have 1kpp extra to spend. So I set out a bounty on the player for 100pp each kill, recurring once a day for 10 days. The key here is that now people will potentially be worth more cash than just the money they carry. The minimum recurring time would be to prevent corpse camping for further rewards. It also means that people can spend larger amounts of money, but not all on one bounty hunter.<br><br>2. Full disclosure to the Warranter - The warranter who puts the price out on someone should have full disclosure of who they are hiring. Perhaps an interface where they set the bounty and all the details (including maybe a note area to say why the person is being hunted?). The hunters then have a window for themselves where they can select a job, and open it for more details, then send an offer of acceptance. The warranter checks the offers and is presented with a list of Name, Class, Race, Titles, Guild Status (even if anon), etc... The warranter needs to be sure it isn't a friend of the person they are trying to get killed.	
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
		<td class="msg_date_cell" valign=bottom nowrap>
