		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			I really don't see this doing much to encourage pvp on Rallos Zek. I've never played on the team servers or Sullon, but the general impression I get (after reading a lot of posts on this forum from people there) is that most? or at least a lot more people than on RZ, are pvping. I think I saw some post about various guilds being at war with each other. <br> This doesn't happen on RZ. Instead of pvp, there is PK and anti-PK. Not to toot my own horn, but in my opinion there is only 1 main pk guild (at lvl 65) on Rallos, The Curse. The very small number of pk's attack everyone, and in turn the anti-pks' only outlet for pvp is to follow the pkers from zone to zone (at least in PoP where it's easy to travel/follow) until the zerg effect gets large enough that the pkers leave the area. I'm not bitching, it's hilarious to see how many people will crawl out of the woodwork to chase us around PoP, and we generally kill a lot more than we get killed. <br> The point I'm getting at is a bounty system won't do anything to encourage more pvp here, when the teams are 95% to 5%. Furthermore, if there's a penalty for dying from a bounty hunter, all that will do is ensure a constant bounty on pkers, not for the sake of a bounty (which is very cool in theoretical roleplaying terms), but for the sole purpose of causing more grief when they die.<br> So, while a bounty system won't get people to pvp more on Rallos (antis never pvp each other, and pks constantly pvp everyone around them already), it might still be interesting, though it won't serve much more of a purpose than an infamy ranking system. The only thing I can think  to add to make it more fun, would be anonymous employers. Let the person who initiates the bounty remain anonymous (I'm not sure how the system is supposed to work, I'm imagining like a mini private message board, where you can list a bounty, people can apply to be bounty hunters, and you can approve/deny them, which would let the employer remain anonymous or not). This way, antis could express which other antis they hate (safe in anonymity), and pkers could earn some cash for doing what they would likely have done anyways, or even try harder to search for/take out that one person amidst the horde of zerglings.	
		</td></tr>
