		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV>OK, so just make the originator of the bounty have to agree to release payment.&nbsp; Clearly this prevents the exploit of a bounty's friend killing him and them splitting the loot.&nbsp; It does create the possibility of valid completed bounties not getting paid,&nbsp;but if people don't pay, hunters will stop going after those people's bounties.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>One other point to consider would be what happens to the bounty if the originator refuses payment.&nbsp; Does it disappear and the neither the originator nor the hunter gets the money?&nbsp; This would basically mean somebody could get a bounty removed from themselves by letting a friend kill them even knowing that payment would be refused.&nbsp; But still, the target still dies.. and people would be much less likely to go through this trouble if nobody is getting money.&nbsp; Alternatively, you could allow the bounty to remain until the originator releases payment to a hunter.&nbsp; This could be exploited to keep a bounty going for ever and ever.&nbsp; I think the answer is to make the bounty disappear if payment is refused to a hunter who has killed the target.&nbsp; The hunter doesn't get paid, and the originator doesn't get his money back.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Lauranathalasa.</DIV>	
		</td></tr>
